facts.text: This appeal arises out of execution proceedings of a decree passed by an arbitrator under the Cooperative Credit Societies Act.

anchor.surface_text: This appeal arises out of execution proceed- ings of a decree passed by an arbitrator under the Co-opera- tive Credit Societies Act.

facts.text: Raja Nandial was a member of the decree-holder society and was also its debtor.

anchor.surface_text: Raja Nandial was a member of the decree-holder society and was also its debtor.

facts.text: A dispute arose between Raja Nandial and the society and the matter was referred to arbitration under the rules governing such societies.

anchor.surface_text: A dispute arose between him and the society and under the rules governing such societies the matter was referred to arbitration.

facts.text: The arbitrator passed a decree against Raja Nandial on the 19th Meher 1352 F. in the sum of Rs. 8,100 payable in equal six monthly instalments with six per cent. interest, the first instalment being payable at the end of Azur 1353 F.

anchor.surface_text: The arbitrator on the 19th Meher 1352 F., passed a decree against him in the sum of Rs. 8,100 payable in equal six monthly instalments with six per cent. interest, the first instalment being payable at the end of Azur 1353 F.

facts.text: On the 2nd Dai 1353 F., the decree was sent for execution to the civil court on a certificate issued under the signature of Moulvi Mohammed Hasan, Madadgar Nazim. The amount recoverable was stated as Rs. 8,100 principal and Rs. 6669-0 interest.

facts.text: On the same day the decree-holder presented an application for execution of the decree to the Civil Court, Balda claiming recovery of Rs. 10,339-14-9 alleging default in the first instalment due in Azur 1353 F making the whole decretal amount recoverable and praying attachment of property.

anchor.surface_text: On the same day the decree-holder present- ed an application for execution of the decree to the Civil Court, Balda. claiming recovery of Rs. 10,339-14-9. It was alleged that as default had been companymitted in the payment of the first instalment due in the month of Azur 1353 F, the whole decretal amount had become recoverable. It was prayed that the property detailed in the application be attached.

facts.text: Default had been committed in the payment of the first instalment due in the month of Azur 1353 F.

anchor.surface_text: It was alleged that as default had been companymitted in the payment of the first instalment due in the month of Azur 1353 F, the whole decretal amount had become recoverable.

facts.text: On 3rd Dai 1353 F., the judgment debtor deposited Rs. 1,000 towards the first instalment in the Office of the Registrar of Co-operative Societies and expressed willingness to deposit any further amount due towards that instalment.

anchor.surface_text: On 3rd Dai 1353 F., i.e., a day after the presentation of the application for execution, the judgment debtor deposited a sum of Rs. 1,000 towards the first instalment in the Office of the Registrar of Co-operative Societies and ex- pressed his will lingness to deposit any further amount that may be due towards that instalment.

facts.text: Nazims office stated that as default committed in first instalment the whole decree due and Rs. 1,000 would not be accepted.

anchor.surface_text: The Nazims office stated in reply that as he had companymitted default in the payment of the first instalment the whole decree had become due and the amount of Rs. 1,000 companyld number be accepted.

facts.text: On the 5th Dai 1353 F, a letter issued by Mohammed Aihsan, Assistant Madadgar Nazim, to Civil Court Balda saying Rs. 1,034 deposited and execution proceedings should be stayed or adjourned.

anchor.surface_text: Subsequentiy, however, on the 5th Dai 1353 F, a letter was issued by one Mohammed Aihsan, Assistant Madadgar Nazim, to the Civil Court, Balda, saying that Rs. 1,034 had been deposited in the Office of the Nizamat Co operative Credit Societies and therefore the proceedings in execution should be stayed or adjourned.

facts.text: Decree-holder raised objection that Registrar had no jurisdiction to stay execution as not executing court.

anchor.surface_text: On receipt of the letter in the civil companyrt, the decree-holder raised an objection that the Registrar had numberjurisdiction to stay execution of the decree as he was number an executing companyrt.

facts.text: Executing court overruled objection and held Registrar retained power under section 42 to stay execution even after certificate.

anchor.surface_text: This objection was overruled by the companyrt and it was held that under the provi- sions of section 42 of the Co-operative Credit Societies Act the Registrar retained the power of staying execution of the award decree even after the issue of a certificate by him.

facts.text: Execution proceedings were stayed.

anchor.surface_text: In the result the execution proceedings were stayed.

facts.text: Appeal taken against the order to Sadar Adalat.

anchor.surface_text: Against this order an appeal was taken to the Sadar Adalat.

facts.text: Sadar Adalat allowed appeal partially: no execution to extent of payment made but executable for future instalments as due; default clause condoned by deposit.

anchor.surface_text: The Sadar Adalat allowed the appeal partially and held that to the extent of the payment made the decree companyld number be executed but it companyld be executed with respect to future instalments as and when they would fall due. It further found that the default clause in the decree must be taken to have been companydoned by the deposit of the first instalment in the office of the Registrar.

facts.text: Decree-holder preferred second appeal to High Court without material success.

anchor.surface_text: The decree-holder preferred a second appeal to the High Court but without any material success.

facts.text: High Court held there had been default in first instalment payment and decree-holder had right to execute whole decree; neither Registrar nor executing court could deprive that right.

anchor.surface_text: The High Court held that there had been a default in the payment of the first instalment and the decree-holder had thus a right to execute the whole decree and that neither the Registrar number the execut- ing companyrt companyld deprive the decree-holder of that right.

facts.text: High Court held Registrar retained jurisdiction to adjourn execution proceedings.

anchor.surface_text: In spite of this finding it took the view that the Registrar still retained jurisdiction to adjourn execution proceed- ings.

facts.text: Judgment-debtor's contention that certificate bad as issued by Madadgar Nazim negatived; Madadgar had delegated powers, defect cured by fresh certificate by Nazim.

anchor.surface_text: The companytention of the judgment-debtor that the cer- tificate was bad as having been issued by a Madadgar Nazim was negatived. It was held that the Madadgar Nazim had delegated powers in this respect and that the defect, if any, stood cured by a fresh certificate signed by the Nazim himself.

facts.text: High Court maintained decision of executing court adjourning execution.

anchor.surface_text: The result was that with these findings the deci- sion of the executing companyrt adjourning the execution pro- ceedings was maintained.

facts.text: Registrar accepted the first instalment after default and asked executing court to stop proceedings.

anchor.surface_text: After a default had been made in the payment of the first instalment and the whole decree debt had become due and execution had been taken out for recovery of the amount, the Registrar accepted the amount of the first instalment and asked the executing companyrt to stop further proceedings.

facts.text: Supreme Court holds Registrar has no jurisdiction as executing court, cannot accept payment or stay execution; executing court to ignore such.

anchor.surface_text: The act of the Regis- trar in accepting the first instalment was a clear trespass on the duties of the executing companyrt. It is only in the executing companyrt where payment towards satisfaction of the decree, the execution of which had been taken out, companyld be made, unless the companyrt passing the decree has also the jurisdiction to execute it. As already indicated,, this jurisdiction is number possessed by the Registrar.

facts.text: Appeal allowed, decisions of courts below set aside, executing court directed to proceed with execution from stage interfered by Registrar's letter.

anchor.surface_text: The result therefore is that this appeal is allowed, the decisions of all the three companyrts below are set aside and the executing companyrt is directed to proceed with the execu- tion of the decree from the stage at which it was interfered with by the letter received from the office of the Regis- trar.
